Dear fellow players,  build a rocket with non-gimballing srbs, the reliant engine or the dart engine to Duna (No need to go back)

Rules

  1. No mods
  2. DLC allowed
  3. No RCS
  4. No Reaction Wheel (Except Command pods)
  5. Rockets Only (No spaceplanes)

On 12/16/2022 at 2:33 AM, The Dark Player said:

Rules

  4. No Reaction Wheel (Except Command pods)

how are we supposed to turn when in space? diffrential thrust?

On 1/11/2023 at 3:02 PM, JcoolTheShipbuilder said:

how are we supposed to turn when in space? diffrential thrust?

Your Kerbals can get out and push? Or is that considered RCS as well?

Edited January 12, 2023 by Klapaucius

Decouplers exert a force on your craft during decoupling. So you could conceivably mount some decouplers around your craft and steer with them.

Edited January 14, 2023 by QF9E

On 1/11/2023 at 3:02 PM, JcoolTheShipbuilder said:

how are we supposed to turn when in space? diffrential thrust?

Actually, it allows for reaction wheels in command pods, so that still gives you a bit.
Is using differential thrust from multiple engines allowed?

It turns out no steering of any kind is necessary. I launched straight up at dawn during a Duna transfer window and when Kerbin passed through the descending node with respect to Duna to land a capsule on the Duna surface without the need for a separate trans Duna Injection burn or any mid-course corrections.

  • Launching straight up at dawn means you're launching into Kerbin's prograde direction around the Sun, which is what is needed for a Hohmann transfer orbit to Duna
  • Launching when Kerbin passes the descending (or ascending node) means you won't miss Duna half an orbit later by flying over or under it.

It did take some fine-tuning of the exact launch time to get this to work, but after half a dozen attempts I found that for my rocket, Year 5, Day 366, 4 hours 08 (which is just before dawn at the KSC) works fine.

Full mission report here: https://imgur.com/a/Y9QpQsg
 

Spoiler

My craft on the pad. Two Thumper SRBs, Reliant core stage.

 

Launching straight up

 

Duna encounter. With a periapse of 13 km you're deep enough inside the atmosphere to aerobrake to a landing on the first pass, without the risk of overshooting into space.

 

 

Stranded on Duna. The mission rules included "No need to get back" so I did not include a return vehicle.
